items.title: Australian tourist dies in Thailand after alleged assault
items.standfirst: I t is unclear what caused the alleged assault to occur
items.content: An Australian tourist has died in a Thailand resort town after allegedly being assaulted by another foreigner.The 58-year-old man, was seen on CCTV engaging in an argument with a 29-year-old man near Phuket on Wednesday night.The younger man is alleged to have assaulted the victim on Prachanukroh Road in Patong, with the Australian sustained serious head injuries.JUST IN: Bystanders tackle driver after car hits pedestrians, takes out wallIt is unclear what led to the assault.According to local media reports, he was taken to Patong Hospital later that night, but he died of his injuries.READ MORE: Company behind Australian cultural icon on verge of being soldThe Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) confirmed they were providing consular assistance to the family.We send our deepest condolences to the family at this difficult time," a DFAT spokesperson told Nine.com.au."They have requested privacy at this time."Thai authorities have arrested a suspect and charged with assault causing death, according to reports in the Bangkok Post.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

clusters.title: Almost 40,000 Budget Direct customers allegedly overcharged $3.3m
clusters.neutral_headline: Almost 40,000 Budget Direct customers allegedly overcharged $3.3m

items.title: Almost 40,000 Budget Direct customers allegedly overcharged $3.3m
items.standfirst: Australia's financial watchdog has taken legal action against the insurer behind the Budget Direct products.
items.content: More than 39,000 Budget Direct customers have allegedly been overcharged $3.3 million due to misleading advertisements, according to Australia's financial watchdog.The Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) has launched legal action in the federal court against the insurer behind Budget Direct's products - Auto and General Services.ASIC alleged that Auto and General Services advertised discounts up to 30 per cent for Budget Direct customers who bought a home, car or motorbike insurance policy online.READ MORE: Company behind Australian cultural icon on verge of being soldHowever, more than 39,000 customers lost the discount after making changes to the policy, like updating their address or changing how often they make payments, during the first year between March 2020 and July 2024, it is alleged.They lost about $100 each and $3.3 million in total. Despite their discounts being removed, the customers allegedly continued to pay for the insurance. ASIC alleged the ads were misleading as the customers were not told they would lose their discounts if they made any changes.The regulator alleged Auto and General Services became aware of the issue as early as 2016 but failed to fix it or notify customers for years." Australians should be able to take insurers at their word, especially when it comes to discounts that influence their decision to take up a policy and compare it to other products in the market," ASIC deputy chair Sarah Court said."We allege Budget Direct's conduct was misleading and deprived tens of thousands of Australians millions of dollars in savings they were promised."READ MORE: VB pins hopes on mid-strength as Aussies drop classic beersAuto and General Services has paid over $3.8 million in remediation, including interest, to the 39,661 affected customers but ASIC will seek declarations and civil penalties from the court.An Auto and General Services spokesperson said it self-reported the incident to ASIC, apologised to and financially compensated the customers."The matter only arose when the customers made an amendment to their policy during the first year – primarily either by replacing their insured car or changing their insured address," the Auto and General Services spokesperson said."In the past two years, Auto and General has invested more than $70 million in improvements to its systems and processes for managing its risk and compliance obligations and to prevent such an issue reoccurring."In addition, since this issue commenced, there has been a significant program of transformation to improve our culture of accountability and compliance."Auto and General is committed to continuing to provide affordable, comprehensive and dependable insurance solutions to our loyal customers."NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here
